  "question": "Kylar went to the store to buy glasses for his new apartment. One glass costs $5, but every second glass costs only 60% of the price. Kylar wants to buy 16 glasses. How much does he need to pay for them?",
  "prompt": "Kylar went to the store to buy glasses for his new apartment. One glass costs $5, but every second glass costs only 60% of the price. Kylar wants to buy 16 glasses. How much does he need to pay for them?\n\nShow your work briefly and put the final answer in \\boxed{}.",
  "gold_answer": "64",
  "generated_text": "To solve this problem, we need to calculate the total cost of buying 16 glasses, considering the pricing rule for every second glass.\n\n**Step 1: Calculate the cost of the first glass.**\nThe first glass costs the full price.\nCost of 1st glass = $\\$5$.\n\n**Step 2: Calculate the cost of every subsequent glass.**\nAccording to the problem, every second glass costs 60% of the price.\nFirst, we determine what \"every second glass\" refers to. Since the first glass is unique, the second glass is the first \"every second\" one.\nPrice of 2nd glass = $60\\%$ of $\\$5 = 0.60 \\times 5 = \\$3$.\n\nThe pattern repeats: every second glass (3rd, 4th, 5th, etc.) costs 60% of $\\$5$.\nSo, the price for any glass $n$ where $n$ is an even number ($2, 4, 6, \\dots$) is $\\$3$.\n\n**Step 3: Calculate the cost of all 16 glasses.**\nThere are 16 glasses in total.\n- The 1st glass costs $\\$5$.\n- The remaining 15 glasses are all \"every second\" glasses, so they all cost $\\$3$.\n\nTotal Cost = (Cost of 1st glass) + (Cost of 15th glasses)\nTotal Cost = $\\$5 + (15 \\times \\$3)$\nTotal Cost = $\\$5 + \\$45$\nTotal Cost = $\\$50$\n\n\\boxed{50}\n",
